This seems to be a &quot;normal&quot; many to many relationship.  Each `Region` can have many different `Tree`s, and each `Tree` can exist in many different `Region`s.

Your Eloquent relationships are already set up, so I would leverage them for all your needs.  You can even encapsulate this in a method belonging to each parent model:

```php
// Region.php

public function countTrees()
{
    return $this-&gt;trees()-&gt;count();
}
```
and
```php
// Tree.php

public function countRegions()
{
    return $this-&gt;regions()-&gt;count();
}
```

Note: by calling `count()` on `regions()` (as opposed to `regions` without the `()`), the computation will be performed in SQL via a single query.  Good for one-off lookups, but not at scale due to n+1 problem.

